<taxonomicName authority="Knisch 1920: 59" authorityName="Knisch" authorityPageNumber="59" authorityYear="1920" box="[151,534,1990,2015]" class="Aves" family="Apodidae" genus="Hydrochous" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="157" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pumilio">
<emphasis box="[151,357,1990,2014]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="157">Hydrochous pumilio</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2460219439" box="[364,534,1990,2015]" collectionCode="RBINS" collectorName="Dr. Drake &amp; Coll. Kraatz &amp; A. Kniz &amp; P. D. Perkins &amp; P. D. Perkins." country="Paraguay" determinerName="Kniz" location="Paraguay" pageId="8" pageNumber="157" specimenCount="10" typeStatus="syntype">
<treatmentCitation author="Knisch, A." box="[364,534,1990,2015]" page="59" pageId="8" pageNumber="157" year="1920">
<bibRefCitation author="Knisch, A." box="[364,534,1990,2015]" pageId="8" pageNumber="157" pagination="55 - 89" refId="ref5572" refString="Knisch, A. (1920) Die exotischen Hydrophiliden des Deutschen Entomologischen Museum (Col.). Archiv fur Naturegeschichte, 85 A, 55 - 89." type="journal article" year="1920">Knisch 1920: 59</bibRefCitation>
</treatmentCitation>
</materialsCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The RBINS kindly provided three 
<typeStatus box="[537,635,153,179]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Knisch" authorityName="Knisch" box="[672,974,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pumilio">
<emphasis box="[672,886,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Hydrochus pumilio</emphasis>
Knisch
</taxonomicName>
, which are part of the Orchymont/Knisch types collection. The 
<typeStatus box="[401,499,189,215]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">syntypes</typeStatus>
are conspecific males. Two of the males had been skillfully dissected by a prior worker, who removed the abdomen of each. The genital segments were in the abdomen, but mysteriously not the male genitalia, which were not otherwise with the specimens. Pol Limbourg (RBINS) very kindly did a very careful search for microslide mounts with the missing male genitalia, but was unable to find any. The third male, nonskillfully dissected by a prior worker, is in four pieces, but did have the male genitalia with the specimen. One of the complete, good male specimens was selected to serve as 
<typeStatus box="[850,956,369,395]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">lectotype</typeStatus>
, and has been so labeled, and habitus and label images provided herein (
<figureCitation box="[493,573,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,2010,2035]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,661,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,633,1985]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Hydrochus pumilio Knisch, habitus of lectotype, and male genitalia of paralectotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3557941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3557941/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Figs. 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[586,636,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 13" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1786,1811]" captionTargetBox="[168,1423,197,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 13A–E. Labels of lectotypes and neotype. (A) Hydrochus metallipes Knisch; (B) Hydrochus pumilio Knisch; (C) Hydrochus purpureus Knisch; (D) Hydrochus tarsalis Chevrolat; (E) Hydrochus secretus Knisch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3557953" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3557953/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">13B</figureCitation>
). The male genitalia figured is from the fragmentary 
<typeStatus box="[1236,1391,405,431]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">paralectotype</typeStatus>
; the male genitalia from this 
<typeStatus box="[424,575,441,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">paralectotype</typeStatus>
is in a glass microvial attached to the pin of the 
<typeStatus box="[1116,1222,441,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">lectotype</typeStatus>
. The non-lectotype 
<typeStatus box="[151,249,477,503]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">syntypes</typeStatus>
have been labeled 
<typeStatus box="[465,630,477,503]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">paralectotypes</typeStatus>
. 
<typeStatus box="[642,754,477,503]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Lectotype</typeStatus>
labels (
<figureCitation box="[842,945,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 13" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1786,1811]" captionTargetBox="[168,1423,197,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 13A–E. Labels of lectotypes and neotype. (A) Hydrochus metallipes Knisch; (B) Hydrochus pumilio Knisch; (C) Hydrochus purpureus Knisch; (D) Hydrochus tarsalis Chevrolat; (E) Hydrochus secretus Knisch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3557953" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3557953/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Fig. 13B</figureCitation>
): “[male symbol] // 
<collectingCountry box="[1166,1269,477,503]" name="Paraguay" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
<collectorName box="[1276,1386,477,503]" pageId="9" pageNumber="158">Dr. Drake</collectorName>
